You are an independent skeptic verifying another agent's investigation of the RBK "Lode" subsystem (fetched-side artifact capture into GAR), in the repo at the current working directory. Do NOT trust their summary — RE-READ the cited files yourself.

Their area: augur (augur/divine reality)

Their findings (JSON):
[
  {
    "claim": "augur does NOT exist in code. There is no rbw-la* tabtarget (the glob ls 'tt/rbw-la*' returns 'no matches found'), no rbld_augur function anywhere in Tools/rbk/, no zipper enrollment, and no theurge const. Every occurrence of 'augur' in the codebase is in spec .adoc files only.",
    "evidence": "ls tt/rbw-la* -> '(eval):1: no matches found'; `grep -rn augur Tools/rbk/` hits only RBS0-SpecTop.adoc, RBSLA-lode_augur.adoc, RBSLD-lode_divine.adoc (no .sh, no .rs files)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "ONE verb (rbld_divine) covers BOTH grains today: with NO argument it enumerates all Lodes; WITH a touchmark argument it inspects one Lode's member tags. The function branches on whether BUZ_FOLIO is empty.",
    "evidence": "rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:31 `local -r z_touchmark=\"${BUZ_FOLIO:-}\"`; line 44 `if test -z \"${z_touchmark}\"; then` ... enumerate-all path (lines 45-116); line 119 comment `# Inspect depth: list the member tags on one Lode package.` then single-Lode tag listing (lines 120-150)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The divine colophon rbw-ld is enrolled with the param1 channel routing to rbld_divine, so the touchmark already arrives as a command-line argument into BUZ_FOLIO. The enrollment description itself states it covers both grains: 'enumerate all, or inspect one Lode's members'.",
    "evidence": "rbz_zipper.sh:89 `buz_enroll RBZ_DIVINE_LODES \"rbw-ld\" \"${z_mod}\" \"rbld_divine\" \"param1\" \"Divine Lodes — enumerate all, or inspect one Lode's members (read-only)\"`",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The theurge consts file defines exactly three Lode colophons — ensconce, divine, banish — and NO augur const. RBTDGC_DIVINE_LODES is 'rbw-ld'.",
    "evidence": "rbtdgc_consts.rs:34-36 RBTDGC_ENSCONCE_BOLE=\"rbw-lE\", RBTDGC_DIVINE_LODES=\"rbw-ld\", RBTDGC_BANISH_LODE=\"rbw-lB\"; grep for AUGUR in that file returns nothing",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "RBSLA describes augur as a separate, fully-specified verb that is written-but-not-coded (not a stub). It has a complete operation body: validate touchmark, authenticate as Director, fetch member tags, decode the lode_vouch provenance envelope, and display with explicit trust-grade posture. RBSLD explicitly defers per-Lode member/vouch detail to augur ('The per-Lode inspect depth ... belongs to {rbtgo_lode_augur}, not here').",
    "evidence": "RBSLA-lode_augur.adoc:13-25 (augur is the single-Lode inspect verb, kind-agnostic), :42-85 (full steps: authenticate, fetch member tags, decode vouch envelope, display trust grade); RBSLD-lode_divine.adoc:15-20 'Divine is lifecycle-grain... The per-Lode inspect depth — member tags and the {rbtga_lode_vouch} envelope — belongs to {rbtgo_lode_augur}, not here.'",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The spec'd augur is RICHER than divine's current inspect branch, not merely a relabel. Divine's inspect branch only lists raw member tags (jq extracts .tags[].name); the spec'd augur additionally extracts the :rbi_vouch manifest, reads its vouch.json layer, and decodes provenance fields (kind, acquired_at, acquired_by, capture_build, trust_grade, members[]) with explicit verified-against-published vs recorded-at-acquisition posture. That envelope-decode is unimplemented anywhere in rbld_divine.",
    "evidence": "rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:131 `jq -r '.tags[]?.name | sub(\".*/tags/\"; \"\")'` then prints MEMBER-TAG rows only; RBSLA-lode_augur.adoc:60-66 'Decode Provenance Envelope ... extract the `:rbi_vouch` manifest ... read its `vouch.json` layer ... fields: kind, acquired_at, acquired_by, capture_build, trust_grade, and members[]' — absent from the divine inspect branch",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "Realizing the augur split is small but non-trivial mechanically: (a) a new tabtarget file tt/rbw-la.<Frontispiece>.sh (same 3-line launcher trampoline as rbw-ld.DirectorDivinesLodes.sh); (b) a buz_enroll line in rbz_zipper.sh for rbw-la -> rbld_augur with param1 channel; (c) a new RBTDGC_AUGUR_* const in rbtdgc_consts.rs; (d) splitting the inspect-one branch (rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:119-150) out of rbld_divine into a new rbld_augur function in rbldl_Lifecycle.sh; (e) trimming rbld_divine to enumerate-only and updating its banner/oparm docs; (f) a ZRBLD_AUGUR_PREFIX in rbld0_Lode.sh kindle alongside the existing DIVINE/BANISH/ENSCONCE prefixes. The vouch-envelope decode the RBSLA spec demands is NOT present in today's inspect branch and would be net-new work if the split is to honor the spec fully.",
    "evidence": "tt/rbw-ld.DirectorDivinesLodes.sh is a 3-line trampoline (BURD_LAUNCHER + exec z-launcher.sh); rbz_zipper.sh:88-90 enrollment pattern; rbld0_Lode.sh:57-63 readonly ZRBLD_*_PREFIX kindle block; rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:119-150 is the extractable inspect-one branch",
    "confidence": "high"
  }
]

Their recommendation_input:
Classification: (c) its own tiny standalone pace — leaning toward (b)/(c) boundary, and notably NOT (a) done and NOT (d) safely deferrable-without-cost. Today rbld_divine is a two-grain verb (enumerate when no folio, inspect-one when a touchmark folio is passed), so the inspect functionality already exists and works; augur is purely a vocabulary/structural split, not a missing capability — EXCEPT that the RBSLA spec defines augur richer than the live inspect branch (it decodes the :rbi_vouch provenance envelope; divine's inspect branch only prints raw member tags). Concrete work to land augur as spec'd: (1) create tt/rbw-la.<Frontispiece>.sh — copy the 3-line trampoline from tt/rbw-ld.DirectorDivinesLodes.sh; (2) add a buz_enroll line in Tools/rbk/rbz_zipper.sh for rbw-la -> rbld_augur, param1 channel; (3) add RBTDGC_AUGUR_* const in Tools/rbk/rbtd/src/rbtdgc_consts.rs; (4) extract rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:119-150 (the inspect-one branch) into a new rbld_augur() in rbldl_Lifecycle.sh, with touchmark-required (use buc_doc_param, not oparm); (5) trim rbld_divine to enumerate-only, drop its oparm touchmark doc and the empty-folio branch; (6) add ZRBLD_AUGUR_PREFIX in rbld0_Lode.sh kindle. Optional-but-spec-mandated extra: implement the :rbi_vouch envelope decode (kind/acquired_at/acquired_by/capture_build/trust_grade/members[] + verified-against-published vs recorded-at-acquisition posture) — net-new, absent from today's code. RECOMMENDATION: If the heat wants strict divine/augur grain separation matching the landed specs, this is a small self-contained pace (steps 1-6) folded easily into the augur work; the envelope-decode portion (the spec's true augur substance) is the only part with real new logic and could justify being its own follow-on if the heat is sequencing the vouch envelope work separately. It is mechanically safe to defer the rename/split (divine already serves inspect-by-touchmark), but doing so leaves a documented divergence: the live `rbw-ld <touchmark>` path and the RBSLA/RBSLD specs disagree on which verb owns the inspect grain.

Independently check the LOAD-BEARING factual claims against the actual files. For each, return whether it holds (with a note citing what you found). Then — most important — state in `corrections` anything they got WRONG, any citation that's off, or anything they MISSED that would change the recommendation. If the recommendation stands as-is, set corrections to an empty string.

